  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "During India's demonetization in November 2016, approximately 99.3% of the invalidated \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes were returned to the banking system by June 2017. This meant that contrary to initial expectations, almost all demonetized currency came back to the banks. \n\nKey points:\n- Total demonetized currency was \u20b915.44 lakh crore\n- About \u20b915.28 lakh crore was returned to banks\n- Only around \u20b916,000 crore (approximately 1-2%) did not return\n\nThe high return rate was unexpected, as the government had anticipated that a significant portion of black money would not be reclaimed. Despite this, the exercise led to increased digital transactions and higher tax compliance.\n\nNote: These figures are based on the Reserve Bank of India's official data from 2017.",
